That day was difficult, but necessary. There‚Äôs no telling where I would be today if I was forced to carry that pregnancy to term. 

Today‚Äîas the right for everyone in this country to make these difficult decisions is stripped away‚Äîis also a difficult day.

I remember laying there awake, repeating ‚ÄòI am so sorry,‚Äô as the doctor performed my abortion. There was very little aftercare for women at that time, and I was forced to suffer in silence due to the shame that society forced upon me and women like me.

Once inside, I saw the other women who were there‚Äîmost of whom were as visibly saddened, worried, and scared as I was.

Despite having access to this critical care, I was still forced to view an ultrasound of the fetus in my womb before I was able to have my procedure.

It had already been heartbreaking enough to arrive at my decision, and now I had to endure the harassment and shame that these protestors hurl at women who find themselves in my situation. I trembled and cried as I hurried past them into the clinic.

I knew I had to have an abortion.

When I arrived at Planned Parenthood, there were protestors lining the street. I was terrified. I sat in my car and cried at the prospect of having to wade through them in order to get the care I needed.

I also went over my personal budget and came to the conclusion that I simply could not afford another child. I was already struggling to afford to feed my children healthy meals, and there was no viable solution that would allow me to carry this pregnancy to term.

I considered adoption, but the father threatened to take the child. considered continuing with the pregnancy, but that would‚Äôve meant maintaining contact with a violent man for the foreseeable future.

I spent the following week in shock and grieving. The tears flowed as I went over every possible scenario, trying to find a way to continue with the pregnancy. I grappled with the history of being taught that abortion was murder‚Äîsomething I know many women will relate to.

I've shared my own story before, but I'm going to tell it again today.

In 2006, as a single mother with three young children, I found myself in a very abusive relationship. As I planned to move to get distance from a dangerous situation, I found out I was pregnant.

I love you, Shalynne. 

You will always be my ‚Äúwhy.‚Äù

It‚Äôs why I‚Äôm running for Congress. 

It‚Äôs why every day, even on days like today, I get up in the morning to keep fighting. Even when it‚Äôs not easy. Because I know that no matter how hard moving forward can be, nothing can be as hard as what my daughter went through.

After losing her, I‚Äôll never be able to go back to my old life again. Not now that my eyes are open. 

I‚Äôll never stop grieving for Shalynne. I‚Äôll also never stop grieving for the tens of thousands of others who die needlessly every year simply due to a lack of health insurance.

Shalynne didn‚Äôt have to die. But she did. At the hands of the almighty dollar.

The last thing I ever said to Shalynne‚Äîas I held her dying body in my arms in her hospital room‚Äîwas, ‚Äúyou will not have died in vain.‚Äù

Shortly after, Shalynne had to fly back to Kansas City to finalize some paperwork for school. The blood clot in her leg dislodged, she began coding, and ultimately died of a massive pulmonary embolism.

They told her to go get insurance and see a specialist; that they were not a doctor‚Äôs office. They refused to treat her, even as she begged them for an MRI and something for the 8 out of 10 pain she was experiencing. And they sent her home.
My daughter was Black, she had sickle cell trait, she was on birth control, and she had just driven 22 hours on a recently injured knee‚Äîall symptoms and risk factors for a blood clot.
I was heading out of town on business, and I remember Shalynne calling me on the phone, crying. ‚ÄúMommy, they‚Äôre not helping me.‚Äù

Shalynne had been living in Kansas City and decided to move home to Las Vegas to be closer to our family and to finish her schooling to become a nurse. When she arrived, she had a red and painfully swollen leg, so we sent her to the local ER to get it looked at.

I had bought into that false narrative that if you just work hard enough, you‚Äôll be safe. I thought we were safe.

But I quickly came to realize that we are all only as safe as the most vulnerable among us.

In June of 2015, I thought I‚Äôd finally made it. After struggling in poverty & as a single mom, I worked my way through college to become the first in my family to earn a degree. Eventually I became a CFO. I remarried, & I was finally able to give my kids the life they deserved.

I‚Äôve told Shalynne‚Äôs story many times, & I tell it for many reasons. To shed light on the horrors & pain caused by profit-driven insurance businesses & corp. hospitals; to keep her memory alive; to grieve & heal; to let others know they‚Äôre not alone; to fight for a better future. https://t.co/j7imqWD3em

Today is tough. June 28th always is.

Six years ago, today, I lost my oldest daughter Shalynne at the hands of our nation‚Äôs broken healthcare system.

After all, marriage is hard work in the best of circumstances. David is my hero. And I am so proud to be part of his family and of the greater family of military spouses.

Factoring in all of these things, plus just the very simple reality of both being apart from your spouse and being alone to deal with everything at home, results in very real and sincere hardship and even trauma for the marriage itself.
Living with these worries is a profound stressor that literally changes your brain.

I've heard the warning sirens go off in the background while on a video call with David, telling him and everyone on the base to take cover. I‚Äôve experienced the absolute pit-of-your-stomach fear that comes with knowing that a current mission might be dangerous.
This is part of the deal and we knew it going in, but it is still an ongoing emotional strain to know that even a simple lazy Sunday can never be guaranteed, let alone a long weekend or vacation.
As a military spouse, you don't get a say in family life the way civilians do. Even if they have been granted leave, an active-duty military member can be called into duty at any time.

As the parent who stays home, it is a huge strain to manage your children's fear and anxiety about their other parent's deployment, both the separation aspect and simply knowing what might happen in a war zone, while managing your own fears and anxieties about the same thing.
The emotional hardship on children is particularly profound during deployment.
This is especially difficult for children with special needs, as the IEP process changes from state to state and it can be a fight just to keep a diagnosis intact with these changing parameters.
Frequent moves are hard on children, both socially and educationally. Not only do they have to make new friends everywhere they move, their educational continuity is forever being disrupted.

Military spouses have ongoing challenges in finding employment and advancing their careers due to constant and unpredictable moves, often having to be the single parent at home, and often being far from family who can help. Covid has only exacerbated these issues of employment.

It is my honor and our privilege to support David in his military career. I am so proud of him. I knew when I married him that it wouldn't be easy to be a military spouse, but I wouldn't change it for the world. Still, I've learned a lot‚Äîand I've learned it the hard way.
